I believe I am encountering a GPU memory leak that the same or similar to the one in issue #707.  I am using the latest Starling and latest Feathers as of Wed Jun 10 11:59:23 EDT 2015 with the latest Adobe Air 18 beta SDK.

Starling latest commit: `68aa0813dc8f822ec07b83401c65f627aecc17d2`
Feathers latest commit: `1a8e67c31d25d88b29d10b1b888bba8055ca967c`

My code does the following...
1. Creates a Image using a texture from Starling's asset manager.
2. Applies a BlurFilter to the image.
3. Adds the image as a child of a sprite.
4. Flatten's the sprite and it's child.
5. On a timer it removes the sprite, disposes it, and recreates it along with the child.  If a filter is used, the app leaks GPU memory.  No filter, no leak.

After a few hundred iterations of the above, Scout reports GPU memory in the mid 500MB range and the app crashes.  No crash (or memory leak) occurs if I comment out the line where I apply the filter (image.filter = new BlueFilter...).

The below code demonstrates the leak.

``` as3
  private var _count:int = 0;
  private var _image:Image;
  private var _container:Sprite;

  // Call the 'run' method to demonstrate the leak.
  // Comment out the below filter line to make the leak go away.
  public function run():void {
    var timer:Timer = new Timer(500, int.MAX_VALUE);
    timer.addEventListener(TimerEvent.TIMER, execute);
    timer.start();
  }

  private function execute(event:TimerEvent):void {
    // Remove and dispose container if it exists.
    if (_container)
      removeChild(_container, true);

    // Create new container.
    _container = new Sprite();
    addChild(_container);

    // Create new image.
    var texture:Texture = AssetManager.instance.getTexture('main_menu_scene/border');
    _image = new Image(texture);

    // Filter for the image.
    var filter:BlurFilter = new BlurFilter(1.5, 1.5, 2);
    _image.filter = filter; // Comment out this line and the memory leak goes away.

    // Attach the image to the container.
    _container.addChild(_image);

    // Flatten container and it's children.
    _container.flatten();

    // Monitor loop count.
    trace(_count++);
  }
```

I think this is not problem about Starling,i post this to Starling forum but without response,so i post it here to get more attention

``` as3
var loader:Loader=new Loader();
loader.addEventListener(ProgressEvent.PROGRESS, onProgress);
loader.load(new URLRequest("a local file url"));
var tf:TextField=new TextField();
stage.addChild(tf);

function onProgress(event:ProgressEvent):void
{
    trace(event.bytesLoaded/event.bytesTotal);
    tf.text=String(event.bytesLoaded/event.bytesTotal);
}
```

the problem is
the trace is print info correctly,but the textfield is not update until progress finish,i think the code is alway running in the onProgress function in one frame,so there is no time for updating the ui,may be load local resource is too fast to update ui.
Such problem is only happen on android, ios is ok.
I have report this problem to Adobe two week ago,but without any response right now.
https://bugbase.adobe.com/index.cfm?event=bug&id=3990146

Because AssetManager use URLLoader to load resource,so when i load large resource,the application is block until load finish and can't show any progress info to user,it is very bad experience

i can use another way to solve such problem for local file,it work well!but AssetManager not use FileStream,and remote resource still a problem.i don't known how to fit this problem right now.

``` javascript
var fileStream:FileStream=new FileStream();
fileStream.addEventListener(ProgressEvent.PROGRESS, onProgress);
fileStream.openAsync(file, FileMode.READ);
everything work well!but AssetManager not use FileStream
```

I find the code in Textfield class,line number start at 218

``` javascript
texture.root.onRestore = function():void
            {
                if (mTextBounds == null)
                    mTextBounds = new Rectangle();

                bitmapData = renderText(scale, mTextBounds);
                texture.root.uploadBitmapData(renderText(scale, mTextBounds));
                bitmapData.dispose();
                bitmapData = null;
            };
```

why call the renderText method 2 times,in my opinion,renderText is a expensive call,am i miss something?

What I'm trying to do:

``` as3
var tex:RenderTexture = new RenderTexture(...); // creates a RenderTexture, which uses two textures internally
tex.draw(imageA);
tex.draw(imageB);

var myRenderer:MyRenderer = new MyRenderer();
myRenderer.renderToTexture(tex); // renders to RenderTexture

tex.draw(imageC); 
```

The problem is, if `imageC` is rendered, the texture is cleared and content created by `myRenderer.renderToTexture(tex)` call is not preserved.

It would be great if there were a method I could call before/after using `myRenderer` to preserve the output it creates.

I came across a blend mode I find quite useful in my project, I think it could also be useful for others.

I called it "mask" and it erases everything that's not under a currently drawn object (it applies this object's alpha channel to the image below).

``` as3
